---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Setup" description="Set up the DeskHub project with seed data and test users for each role.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Setup</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Fifth time. You know this. Create the folder, open VS Code, launch Claude Code, hand over the files.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-3">Create the project</h2>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ mkdir -p ~/dev && cd ~/dev
$ mkdir deskhub && cd deskhub
$ code .`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-3 mt-8">Set up the branching strategy</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This project uses a staging/production pipeline. Create a <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">develop</code> branch — this is where feature branches merge first. After testing on staging, you promote to <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">main</code> for production.</p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ cd ~/dev/deskhub
$ git init
$ git checkout -b main
$ git checkout -b develop`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mt-4 mb-8">Feature branches merge into <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">develop</code>. When staging is verified, <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">develop</code> merges into <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">main</code> for production deployment.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-3 mt-8">Launch Claude Code and hand over the files</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Open the terminal in VS Code, run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">claude</code>, and give it everything:</p>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Here's the CLAUDE.md for the project:

[Paste CLAUDE.md here]

And here's the BACKLOG.md:

[Paste BACKLOG.md here]`}</CodeBlock>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>No external API keys needed.</strong> Unlike P3's email service or P4's Stripe and Google Maps, authentication is built-in — there are no third-party services to configure. The JWT library, password hashing, and role middleware are all part of your own codebase.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Seed data</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">The setup should create test users for each role with known passwords. You'll switch between these constantly during development and adversarial testing.</p>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-muted">
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Email</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Role</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Password</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">member@test.com</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Member</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">testpass123</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">member2@test.com</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Member</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">testpass123</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">admin@test.com</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Admin</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">testpass123</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">owner@test.com</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Owner</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">testpass123</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Two member accounts — you need both to test data isolation. Create bookings as member 1, log in as member 2, and verify they can't see them.</p>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>These are development-only seed users.</strong> Real production passwords must be strong. The seed data is just for testing — it lets you switch between roles quickly without creating accounts manually each time.</p>
  </Callout>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mt-6 mb-4">Start Ticket 1. You know what to do.</p>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: building</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Project set up. Time to build — with adversarial testing at every step.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/5/implementation/building"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Building →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
